{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = [[File:Tsu jinja2009-3.jpg|250px|Tsu Shrine]] | name = Tsu Shrine (津神社) | location = Sogaya, Yashiki 1631, Gifu City, Gifu Prefecture, Japan | coordinates = {{Coord|35|25|42.48|N|136|43|15.68|E|scale:30000|display=inline,title|name=Tsu Shrine}} | deities = {{ill|Agata Sumi no Mikoto|ja|縣須美命|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|12=draft|12=draft}} | type = {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} | established = 6th century | architecture = | festivals = | rituals = }}
'''Tsu Shrine''' (津神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Gifu City|ja|岐阜市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Gifu Prefecture, Japan. It is situated west of the {{ill|Shima Bridge|ja|島大橋|12=draft|12=draft}} over the {{ill|Ijira River|ja|伊自良川|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The shrine is believed to correspond to the {{ill|Hōgō-gun Tsu Shrine|ja|方県津神社|1=Katagatatsu Shrine|12=draft|12=draft}}, an {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft|12=draft}}-listed shrine of the Hōgō District in {{ill|Mino Province|ja|美濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, there are competing theories about the true identity of the Hōgō-gun Tsu Shrine, with other candidates including {{ill|Hōgō Tsu Shrine|ja|方県津神社|1=Katagatatsu Shrine|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Agata Shrine (Gifu)|ja|縣神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == According to shrine tradition, Tsu Shrine was established during the reign of {{ill|Empress Suiko|ja|推古天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} with a deity transferred from Tsu in {{ill|Ano District|ja|安濃郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft|12=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Tsu, Mie|ja|津市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Mie Prefecture). The original shrine from which it was transferred is unknown.
An alternative theory suggests the shrine's origin lies in a transfer from {{ill|Shiozu Shrine|ja|潮津神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kaga Province|ja|加賀国|12=draft|12=draft}} (modern-day {{ill|Kaga, Ishikawa|ja|加賀市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ishikawa Prefecture).
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was known as "Hōgō Tsu Daimyōjin." In 1873 (Meiji 6), it was renamed "Tsu Shrine."
== Enshrined Deities == * {{ill|Agata Sumi no Mikoto|ja|縣須美命|12=draft|12=draft}} (details unknown) * {{ill|Takenouchi no Sukune|ja|武渟川別命|12=draft|12=draft}}
== location == * Sogaya, Yashiki 1631, Gifu City, Gifu Prefecture, Japan
== Access == * By {{ill|Gifu Bus|ja|岐阜乗合自動車|12=draft|12=draft}}: ** From JR {{ill|Gifu Station|ja|岐阜駅|12=draft|12=draft}} (north exit, bus terminal platform 8) or {{ill|Meitetsu Gifu Station|ja|名鉄岐阜駅|12=draft|12=draft}} (west, platform 6), take "O80 Riverside Mall (via Ōnawa Bridge)" or "O85 Ōno Bus Center" to "Sogaya Higashi" stop. ** Alternatively, take the Sogaya Line ("K25 Higashikaiden" or "K26 Higashikaiden via Terada Garden") to "Sogaya-guchi" stop from JR Gifu Station (north exit, bus terminal platform 8) or Gifu Bus Terminal (south of Meitetsu Gifu Station, platform D).
